      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> nasf, I think if the OI Scrub wasn't allowed to get so far ahead of layout verification then cache flushing wouldn't be a problem. I think part of the current problem is that OI Scrub is not limited by the async window and it can produce too many lfsck_layout_req's to fill the MDS memory and push OSD objects out of cache.\nIf OI scrub was throttled when it got too far ahead of the layout engine then the OSD objects would still be in cache even without any reference on them.\nThat is something for a separate patch I think, since this one should land as-is to at least get the benefit of not keeping a reference on the parent object.\n\nAndreas, if the OI scrub is under urgent mode, such as rebuild/recreate OI files, then it will run as fast as possible, under such case, the OI scrub may be much ahead of other up layer LFSCK component (namespace LFSCK/layout LFSCK). But if it is NOT under urgent mode, then the OI scrub speed will be controlled via the OSD layer pre-fetching cache size that is SCRUB_WINDOW_SIZE (1024). So the OI scrub will be at most SCRUB_WINDOW_SIZE ahead of the other up layer LFSCK component.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    }
